{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636513"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:29:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:29:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17588"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17588"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71450"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10278"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56959"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10094"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24020"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24120"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71450"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin C (ascorbic acid) is an essential water-soluble vitamin that must be obtained through dietary sources. It is absorbed in the gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its absorption?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Simple diffusion in the small intestine","Active transport in the small intestine","Active transport in the stomach only","Facilitated diffusion in the large intestine","Passive diffusion throughout the entire intestine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin C is absorbed via \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive transport in the small intestine\u003C/strong\u003E using sodium-dependent carriers. These transporters, specifically sodium-dependent vitamin C transporters (SVCT), actively move vitamin C against its concentration gradient using energy from the sodium gradient. This process is saturable, meaning absorption efficiency decreases with higher doses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion throughout entire intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - As a charged molecule at physiological pH, vitamin C cannot freely diffuse across cell membranes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport in stomach only\u003C/strong\u003E - The acidic environment of the stomach is not suitable for vitamin C absorption\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitated diffusion in large intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - Vitamin C absorption occurs primarily in the small intestine, not the large intestine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple diffusion in small intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - The charged nature of vitamin C prevents simple diffusion across cell membranes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this mechanism explains why taking very large doses of vitamin C supplements is inefficient - the transport system becomes saturated, leading to decreased absorption of additional vitamin C.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) is actively absorbed in the small intestine via sodium-dependent transporters.","Vitamin C absorption is most efficient at lower doses; higher doses have reduced absorption efficiency.","The small intestine can only absorb a limited amount of vitamin C per dose due to transporter saturation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. Available from: https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56959"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17588"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56959"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T17:02:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T17:03:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10278"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71450"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"